opAccountSummary.premierTrackerLearnAboutText:
• Premier qualifying flights: Premier qualifying flights (PQF) are based on the number of paid flight segments traveled on United, United Express®, and select airline partners

  • Premier qualifying points: Premier qualifying points (PQP) are based on the base fare and surcharge of flight purchases, along with most seating purchases and paid upgrades.

  • A minimum of four paid flight segments on United and/or United Express® is required in order to qualify for any Premier level. Certain exemptions apply.

  • Lifetime miles are earned based on the flight distance of United and United Express®-operated flights.

Full qualification terms and conditions

empTravelTypes.advisory:
London or Tokyo, New York or San Francisco – wherever you’re traveling for work, we want you to book company business travel responsibly.

  • If your schedule permits and you are not declaring “must ride” status, choose a flight that is not at or over capacity.
  • If your plans have changed and you no longer need to travel, make sure to cancel in advance the bookings you don’t need. Cancellations made within one hour of scheduled departure are reported to your leadership team.
  • Avoid creating duplicate bookings. Double bookings are subject to automatic cancellation and are reported to your leadership team.
  • You must comply with all local entry requirements. For more information, please visit United’s Travel Ready Center.

For more information, check out the Company Business Travel Policy .

You are creating a positive-space booking which will take a revenue seat out of inventory that could otherwise have been sold. Please book positive-space travel responsibly.

  • Booking multiple positive-space bookings to the same or similar destination for the same business trip is not permitted.

Examples: Holding positive space for ORD PEK and IAD PEK or IAH LHR and IAH CDG for the same trip are considered duplicate bookings, as it is only possible to fly one. Holding two positive-space bookings for IAH ORD at different times for the same trip is considered a duplicate booking. Duplicate bookings are subject to automatic cancellation.

  • Consider other flight options for segments at or over capacity if your schedule permits and you are not considered must ride.
  • Cancel your positive space booking promptly if you determine the flights are no longer needed.
  • No-Shows and last minute cancellations should be carefully avoided.
  • Duplicate and no-show bookings are reported to VP of each division.
  • To review your current positive space bookings select the “Travel Plans” tab.

The Emergency Pass Travel policy can be found on Flying Together > Travel > Travel homepage > IN THIS SECTION > Types of travel> Emergency travel. Have a question? Try Help Hub to search for answers to commonly asked questions about this policy, submit requests to the Employee Travel Center and get real-time updates on your requests.

You are creating a positive-space booking which will take a revenue seat out of inventory that could otherwise have been sold. Please book positive-space travel responsibly.

Pilots:
The boarding priority of Training Travel (PS0T) may only be selected for travel directly related to simulator recurrent training assignments (CQ) and only for travel between your primary residence or your Base and the CQ event. For all other travel related to training that is not CQ, such as training for new equipment, please select normal Business Travel (PS5B).

Flight attendants:
The boarding priority of Training Travel (PSOU) may only be selected for travel directly related to recurrent training assignments (CQ), equipment training or purser training for pmUA flight attendants and only for travel between your primary residence or your Base and the training event.
For pmCO flight attendants travelling to training, you do not need to list for travel because the deadhead travel is built into the training pairing from the base to the training location. For pmCO only, if you wish to travel from your home to training, contact crew scheduling to have FAKE placed in your deadhead then list for training travel through employeeRES.

  • Booking multiple positive-space bookings to the same or similar destination for the same business trip is not permitted.

Examples: Holding positive space for ORD PEK and IAD PEK or IAH LHR and IAH CDG for the same trip are considered duplicate bookings, as it is only possible to fly one. Holding two positive-space bookings for IAH ORD at different times for the same trip is considered a duplicate booking. Duplicate bookings are subject to automatic cancellation.

  • Cancel your positive space booking promptly if you determine the flights are no longer needed.
  • No-Shows and last minute cancellations should be carefully avoided.
  • Duplicate and no-show bookings are reported to VP of each division.
  • To review your current positive space bookings select the “My Travel Plans” tab.

The Company Business Policy can be found on Flying Together > Travel > Company Business. Questions regarding this policy can be directed to etc@united.com.
